g 4. Historical sketch. Dyrrhachium to Pharsalia.

After the double disaster which in May, 48 B.c.³‚ Caesar had brought upon himself by his audacious attempt to blockade a superior with an inferior force, his position round Dyrrhachium was untenable; and he at once decided to withdraw into the interior. His route of march was across the river Genusus through Asparagium to Apollonia, his first destination. His retreat was rapid, and effected without loss; indeed the pursuing Pompeians suffered severely in a cavalry engagement on the banks of the Genusus.
